ğŸ”· Generics in Java
ğŸ“Œ Definition

Generics allow us to write a class, interface, or method that can work with different data types in a type-safe way.

ğŸ‘‰ It means:
You can create a class that works with Integer, String, Double, etc.
Without rewriting the code again and again.

ğŸ¯ Why Do We Need Generics?

Before Generics (Java 1.5):

We used:

ArrayList list = new ArrayList();
list.add("Hello");
list.add(10);


Now problem is:

Mixed data types.

Need typecasting.

Compile-time safety is not there.

âŒ Without Generics Problem
ArrayList list = new ArrayList();
list.add("Bitu");

String name = (String) list.get(0);


You must typecast â†’ risky ğŸ˜“
If wrong casting â†’ Runtime Error.

âœ… With Generics
ArrayList<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
list.add("Bitu");

String name = list.get(0);


âœ” No typecasting needed
âœ” Compile-time checking
âœ” Type safety

ğŸ§  Real-Life Analogy

Think of Generics like a lunch box with label:

If label says "Rice" ğŸš â†’ Only rice allowed

If label says "Fruits" ğŸ â†’ Only fruits allowed

No mixing!

Same:

ArrayList<String>
ArrayList<Integer>

ğŸ”‘ Generic Class
âœ… Syntax
class Box<T> {
    T value;

    void setValue(T value) {
        this.value = value;
    }

    T getValue() {
        return value;
    }
}

ğŸ” Use It
public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Box<Integer> obj = new Box<>();

        obj.setValue(100);
        System.out.println(obj.getValue());
    }
}

ğŸ” Step-by-Step

<T> â†’ Type parameter

T acts like placeholder

At runtime â†’ replaced with actual type

ğŸ”‘ Generic Method

You can also make methods generic.

âœ… Example
class Test {

    public static <T> void display(T data) {
        System.out.println(data);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        display(10);
        display("Bitu");
        display(3.14);
    }
}

ğŸ”‘ Multiple Type Parameters
class Pair<T, U> {
    T first;
    U second;
}


Use:

Pair<String, Integer> p = new Pair<>();

âš  Important Points

âœ” Generics work only with Objects
âŒ Not with primitive types

Wrong:

